<h1>Edgar Rice Burroughs<br />Is Back</h1>

<h2>in a new, never-before-published hardcover!</h2>

<!--hr width="100%" /-->
<p class="center">
 <img src="ftdj_4in.jpg" border="0" height="177" width="288" /><br />
<font size="-1">
<a href="ftdj_lrg.jpg"> Art by Danny Frolich (click for larger cover image)</a><br />
<font color="#000099">
including eighteen new interior illustrations
</font>
</font><br />
<img src="ftbwsamp.jpg" align="top" border="0" height="162" width="483" /></p><p>

<!--START FORGOTTEN TALES TEXT-->
</p><p>
<font color="#cc0000" size="+2"> <b> <i> Available now! &#8212;</i></b></font></p>

<center>
<b> <i> 
<font color="#0000ff" face="Times New Roman,Times" size="+2"> Forgotten Tales<br />
of Love and Murder</font><br />
by<br />
Edgar Rice Burroughs
</i></b>
</center>

<p class="center"> <font color="#cc0000"> Limited to 1,045 copies &#8212; click <a href="ft-order.htm" target="_blank"> here</a> to order</font></p>
<p class="center"> <font color="#cc0000">
Read about the <a href="#TProject">Tarzana Project</a>
</font>
</p>

<p> This book collects in a single volume all of Edgar Rice Burroughs&#8217;
non-Tarzan short stories and mystery puzzles, most of which have never
before appeared in print:</p>

<ul>
<li>&#8220;An Autobiographical Sketch&#8221; (originally published in <i> Amazing Stories</i> , June, 1941).</li>

<li>&#8220;Jonathan&#8217;s Patience,&#8221; an ironic, previously overlooked tale that appears to predate Burroughs&#8217; professional work.</li>

<li>&#8220;The Avenger&#8221; (1912), a dark, violent story of revenge.</li>

<li>&#8220;For The Fool&#8217;s Mother&#8221; (1912), ERB&#8217;s first Western.</li>

<li>&#8220;The Little Door&#8221; (1917), a powerful tale of love, war, and horror.</li>

<li>&#8220;Calling All Cars&#8221; (1931), murder and romance in the hills of Los Angeles.</li>

<li>&#8220;Elmer&#8221; (1936), a defrosted caveman comes to Hollywood. (This is
ERB&#8217;s original version of the story his magazine editor revised into
&#8220;The Resurrection of Jimber-Jaw.&#8221;)</li>

<li>&#8220;The Strange Adventure of Mr. Dinnwiddie&#8221; (1940), humor, seduction, and intrigue aboard an ocean liner bound for Hawaii.</li>

<li>&#8220;Misogynists Preferred&#8221; (1941), demonstrating what happens when a gaggle of woman-hating men meets a covey of man-hating women.</li>

<li>&#8220;Uncle Bill&#8221; (1944), a tale of horror in everyday life.</li>

<li>&#8220;The Red Necktie&#8221; (circa 1932), a stand-alone mystery puzzle.</li>

<li>&#8220;Murder: A Collection of Short Murder Mystery Puzzles&#8221; (circa
1932-1940), seven fictional puzzles, featuring ERB&#8217;s last series
character to appear in book form &#8212; Police Inspector Muldoon &#8212; and his
trusted biographer and sidekick, Edgar Rice Burroughs!</li>

<li>&#8220;The Dupuyster Case&#8221; (circa 1932), an unfinished Muldoon mystery puzzle.</li>
</ul>
This 283-page first edition also contains eight full-page and ten
smaller illustrations by award-winning artist Danny Frolich. Limited to
1,045 copies, of which approximately 1,000 will be offered for sale, it
can be ordered for $49.95 plus shipping and handling until September 30, 2009 ($59.95 thereafter).<br />
<br />
 

<p> (If your primary interest is in reading the book and you don&#8217;t feel
you need to own a copy, why not print out our order form/flyer, take it
to your local library, and request that they order a copy for you?)
</p>

